<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920106-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>920106-0028.</DOCID><HL>   Oil Production in Siberia   Dropped About 15% in `91   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>01/06/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)PETROLEUM (PET)</IN><NS>INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND ANALYSIS (IEN)PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)</NS><RE>ARABIAN PENINSULA (ARA)EASTERN EUROPE (EEU)EUROPE (EU)FAR EAST (FE)MIDDLE EAST (ML)SAUDI ARABIA (SA)COMMONWEALTH OF INDEPENDENT STATES (UR)</RE><LP>   MOSCOW -- Oil production in Siberia fell by about 15% in1991 and is expected to plunge to even lower levels thisyear, according to Soviet media.   Yuri Lesovoi, deputy head of the Regional Economic AffairsBoard in the oil-rich Tyumen region, said Siberian oilproduction declined by 50 million tons to 305 million tons in1991. Production is expected to fall to about 260 milliontons this year, the Russian Information Agency reported.</LP><TEXT>   Western Siberia was the largest oil-producing area in theformer Soviet Union, accounting for about 60% of thecountry's total output. Rapidly falling production in theformer Soviet Union has cut severely into the region'sforeign currency earnings, adding to the economic woes of thenew Commonwealth of Independent States.   Analysts have said that independent Russia's oilproduction may soon be surpassed by that of Saudi Arabia.They believe oil production in Russia can be stabilized onlyif equipment throughout Siberia is modernized, according tothe semi-official Russian Information Agency.   Russian President Boris Yeltsin recently passed a decreeallowing oil producers to privately sell 20% of their oil toraise cash to improve their gear.</TEXT></DOC>